observations.recommendation:
Trace the causes of the variances to take up necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts and/or updating the records of the Treasury;


Maintain the PCs and PPELCs so that reconciliation of items and balances between the offices can be undertaken before the submission of the reports; and


Submit the copy of the RPCPPE of CY 2023 duly signed by the concerned officials.   



Consider recognizing the provision of impairment losses in the books of accounts for the damaged/unserviceable assets;




Update the PPE records and delete the lost items based on COA decision granting the Request for Relief from Accountability so that it will not carry over in the next year’s report.

Submit the RPCI to the Audit Team for evaluation;


Maintain the SLC and SC of each item of the supplies, respectively, to facilitate monitoring and reconciliation; and

Investigate the causes of the delay of the submission of the report despite prior year’s audit observations so that appropriate actions/measures can be undertaken to prevent the recurrence of the deficiency.

Deduct the liquidated damages from any money due or which may become due to the supplier, or collect from any securities or warranties posted by the supplier and submit a written explanation on the payment made despite the absence of the IAR;

Submit the PAR and/or RIS for the rest of the items not included in the initially issued PAR for evaluation; and

Submit explanation on the preparation of the contract/PO beyond the allowable days for the activity.

2.10 We recommended and Management agreed to:
require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which data should come from the RPTAR or Taxpayer’s Index Card maintained at the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the certified list to serve as basis in recording the RPTReceivable and SET Receivable accounts in the books;
require the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables based on the list furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in order to recognize in the books an accurate and reliable data pursuant to 20 of the NGAS Manual, Volume 1; and
finally, require the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to reconcile their records.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
direct the Municipal Agriculturist to conduct physical count of all the biological assets taking into consideration their biological transformation and maintain and update the records for breeding stocks and submit a report thereon to the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer so that the respective records of these offices can be updated and reconciled purposely to present fairly the accounts in the financial statements;
require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the books of accounts to reflect the correct fair value of the biological assets based on the results of inventory made by the Municipal Agriculturist and continue to maintain WOABSLC for each type of breeding stocks with sufficient details;
assess the contents of the Dispersal Agreement between the Municipality and recipient and revise as necessary in order to protect the interest of both parties;
require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify future inflow of cash relative to payments from recipients as Other Receivables and wholly derecognize the breeding stocks measured at fair market values. Likewise, investigate the cause of inclusion of negative amount of ₱1,400.00 under swine dispersal; and
henceforth, require the accountable officer the immediate submission of the petition for relief from accountability together with its complete supporting documents.
